                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" hclass="sense" fkcefr="c2" id="adder_sng_1" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" hclass="sensetop" htag="span"><span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">a small snake, often with marks in the shape of diamonds on its back. <span class="dh">Adders</span> are the only poisonous snakes in Britain.</span></span> <span class="xrefs" hclass="xrefs" xt="see" htag="span"><span class="prefix">see also</span> <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/puff-adder" title="puff adder definition"><span class="xr-g" bord="n" dict="all" href="puffadder_e"><span class="xh">puff adder</span></span></a></span><span class="topic-g"><span class="prefix">Topics </span><a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/topic/animals?level=c2" title="Topic animals"><span class="topic" href="l2:animals:animals?cefr=c2"><span class="topic_name">Animals</span><span class="topic_cefr">c2</span></span></a></span><div class="collapse" htag="div" hclass="collapse"><span class="unbox" id="adder_unbox_1" unbox="wordorigin"><span class="box_title">Word Origin</span><span class="body"><span class="p">Old English <span class="ei">nædre</span> ‘serpent, adder’, of Germanic origin; related to Dutch <span class="ei">adder</span> and German <span class="ei">Natter</span>. The initial <span class="ei">n</span> was lost in Middle English by wrong division of <span class="ei">a naddre</span>; compare with <span class="eb">apron</span> and <span class="eb">umpire</span>.</span></span></span></div>    <div id="ring-links-box">
